{{Infobox person |name = Gallus Mag |birth_name = |birth_date = ? |birth_place = [[England]], [[United Kingdom]] |death_date = ? |death_place = |residence = [[Water Street (Manhattan)|Water Street]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]] |nationality = British American |other_names = |known_for = Being 6-foot-tall plus female [[Bouncer (doorman)|bouncer]] at a 19th century [[New York City]] [[Water Street (Manhattan)|Water Street]] [[bar (establishment)|bar]] called "The Hole in the Wall", who figures prominently in New York City [[folklore]]. The bar is still present at [https://infamousnewyork.com/category/south-street-seaport/ 279 Water Street], and called the Bridge Cafe. |occupation = bar bouncer }}
'''Gallus Mag''' (real name unknown) was a 6-foot-tall plus female [[Bouncer (doorman)|bouncer]] at a 19th century [[New York City]] [[Water Street (Manhattan)|Water Street]] [[bar (establishment)|bar]] called "[[The Hole in the Wall (New York bar)|The Hole in the Wall]]", who figures prominently in New York City [[folklore]]. The name "Gallus"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/gallus |title= gallus |website= Wiktionary |access-date= 2017-06-07 }}</ref> originated from the unladylike men's [[suspenders]] she was fond of wearing, and Mag or Meg was likely her forename.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/nyregion/13fyi.html Profile], Nytimes.com; accessed December 25, 2016.</ref>
==Bar bouncer== [[Herbert Asbury]]'s book ''[[The Gangs of New York (book)|The Gangs of New York]]'' thus described her:
:''"It was her custom, after she'd felled an obstreperous customer with her club, to clutch his ear between her teeth and so drag him to the door, amid the frenzied cheers of the onlookers. If her victim protested she bit his ear off, and having cast the fellow into the street she carefully deposited the detached member in a jar of alcohol behind the bar…. She was one of the most feared denizens on the waterfront and the police of the period shudderingly described her as the most savage female they'd ever encountered."''<ref>[[Herbert Asbury|Asbury, Herbert]]. ''The Gangs of New York''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf, 1928; {{ISBN|978-1-56025-275-7}}</ref>
==In popular culture== *Gallus Mag's was the name of a bar near Corlears Hook in the mid- to late 19th century.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= River Thieves |url= https://www.newspapers.com/image/60760711/?terms=%22gallus%2Bmag%22 |work= The Brooklyn Daily Eagle |location= Brooklyn, NY |date= 1874-01-20 |access-date= 2017-06-12}}</ref> *In the 2002 [[Martin Scorsese]] film ''[[Gangs of New York]]'', a character, a female street gangster, Hell-Cat Maggie, played by [[Cara Seymour]], is a composite of Gallus Mag, the real-life [[Hell-Cat Maggie]], and the apparently fictional [[Sadie Farrell|Sadie the Goat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldsaltblog.com/2014/06/will-the-real-gallus-mag-or-meg-stand-up-no-biting-please |title=Will the Real Gallus Mag, or Meg, Stand Up? No Biting, Please - Old Salt BlogOld Salt Blog |website=Oldsaltblog.com |date=2014-06-04 |accessdate=2016-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nypress.com/print.cfm?content_id=3753 |title=The Gangs of New York |author=Estep, Maggie |date=2001-03-01 |publisher=[[New York Press]] |accessdate=2016-12-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040107032757/http://www.nypress.com/print.cfm?content_id=3753 |archivedate=2004-01-07 |df= }}</ref> *Gallus Mag was portrayed by [[Ronda Rousey]] in the "Scoundrels" episode of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Drunk History]]''.
