'''James Charles "Jim" Lehrer''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|l|ɛər|ər}}; born May 19, 1934)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/lehrer,_jim |title=Oxford English Dictionary Entry for Jim Lehrer |publisher=Oxford Dictionaries |date=1 December 2016 |accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> is an American journalist and a novelist.

Lehrer is the former [[executive editor|Executive Editor]] and a former [[news anchor|News Anchor]] for the ''[[PBS NewsHour]]'' on [[PBS]], and is known for his role as a Debate Moderator in U.S. Presidential Election campaigns. He is an author of numerous fiction and non-fiction books that draw upon his experience as a newsman, along with his interests in history and politics.<ref name=PBSbio />

==Early years==
Lehrer was born in [[Wichita, Kansas]]—the son of Lois Catherine (née Chapman), a bank clerk; and Harry Frederick Lehrer, a bus station manager.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jim Lehrer Biography (1934–) |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/51/Jim-Lehrer.html |publisher=film reference |year=2011 |accessdate=3 May 2011}}</ref> He attended middle school in [[Beaumont, Texas]], and graduated from [[Thomas Jefferson High School (San Antonio, TX)]] where he was a sports editor for the ''Jefferson Declaration''. He graduated with an A.A. from [[Victoria College (Texas)|Victoria College]] in Texas, and a B.J. from the [[Missouri School of Journalism]] at the [[University of Missouri]] in 1956.

After graduation from college, Lehrer joined the [[United States Marine Corps]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Jim Lehrer |title=Jim Lehrer Reflects on Marines at Museum Dedication |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/military/july-dec06/marines_11-10.html |publisher=[[PBS NewsHour]] |date=November 10, 2006 |accessdate=2011-05-03}}</ref> and attributes his service and travels with helping him to look past himself and feel a connection to the world that he would not have otherwise experienced.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jim Lehrer |url=http://www.hno.harvard.edu/gazette/daily/2006/06/08-lehrerspeech.html |title=Commencement speech of Jim Lehrer |publisher=Harvard University |date=June 8, 2008 |accessdate=28 September 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

==Career==
In 1959, Lehrer began his career in journalism at ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' in Texas.  Later, he worked as a Reporter for the ''[[Dallas Times-Herald]]'', where he covered the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy]] in 1963. There, he was a Political Columnist for several years, and in 1968 he became the City Editor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Jim-Lehrer 
|title=Jim Lehrer - American Journalist and Author |date=30 August 2011 |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica 
|website=Britannica.com |accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref>

Lehrer began his television career at [[KERA-TV]] in Dallas, Texas, as the Executive Director of Public Affairs, an On-air Host, and Editor of a nightly news program. He moved to [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] in Washington, D.C., to become the Public Affairs Coordinator, a member of Journalism Advisory Board, and a Fellow at the [[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]] (CPB).  He worked as a Correspondent for the National Public Affairs Center for Television (NPACT) where he met [[Robert MacNeil]]. In 1973, they covered the [[Senate Watergate hearings]] and the revelation of the [[Watergate scandal#Senate Watergate hearings revelation of the Watergate Tapes|Watergate Tapes]] broadcast, live on PBS. Lehrer covered the [[House Judiciary Committee]]'s [[Watergate scandal#Final investigations and resignation|impeachment inquiry of President Richard Nixon]].

In October 1975, Lehrer became the Washington Correspondent for the "[[Robert MacNeil]] Report" on Thirteen/[[WNET]] New York. Two months later on December 1, 1975, he was promoted to co-anchor, and the program was accordingly renamed "The MacNeil/Lehrer Report". In September 1983, Lehrer and MacNeil relaunched their show as ''The MacNeil/Lehrer NewsHour'' which, after MacNeil's departure in 1995, was renamed ''The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer'', and in 2009 became the ''PBS NewsHour''.<ref name=PBSbio>{{cite web |title=About Us: Jim Lehrer, Executive Editor |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/spc/news/jimlehrer/ |publisher=The PBS NewsHour |year=2012 |accessdate=4 February 2013}}</ref>

Lehrer underwent a heart valve surgery in April 2008, and, while he recuperated, [[Ray Suarez]] anchored in his stead until his return on June 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite news | author=The Associated Press | title=''NewsHour'' Anchor Jim Lehrer Has Heart Surgery | url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/04/25/arts/TV-Lehrer-Surgery.php | work=The International Herald Tribune | date=25 April 2008 | accessdate=26 September 2008}}</ref>

On June 6, 2011, Lehrer stepped down as anchor of the ''PBS NewsHour''; however, he continued to moderate the Friday news analysis segments, and continued to be involved with the show's production company, MacNeil/Lehrer Productions.<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Farhi |title=Jim Lehrer to step down from daily broadcast at 'NewsHour' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/jim-lehrer-to-step-down-from-daily-broadcast-at-pbs-newshour/2011/05/12/AFS5VwyG_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 12, 2011 |accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>

Lehrer's has received several awards and honors throughout his career in journalism, including several [[Emmy Award|Emmys]]; the [[Peabody Award|George Foster Peabody Broadcast Award]]; a [[William Allen White]] Foundation Award for Journalistic Merit; and the [[University of Missouri School of Journalism]]'s Medal of Honor.  In 2004, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Journalism degree by [[McDaniel College]].[http://www.mcdaniel.edu/]<ref>''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' - "McDaniel's Commencement is Saturday; Jim and Kate Lehrer to Get Honorary Degrees," 16 May 2004.</ref>

==Presidential debate moderator==
Lehrer has been involved in several U.S. Presidential Debate-related projects, including the ''Debating Our Destiny'' Documentaries in 2000 and 2008, that feature excerpts of exclusive interviews with many of the Presidential and Vice Presidential candidates since 1976.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/spc/debatingourdestiny/ 
|title=Jim Lehrer Hosts Debating our Destiny |publisher= MacNeil/Lehrer Productions in association with the Commission on Presidential Debates and WETA |website=PBS.org |date=31 December 2008 |accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> Nicknamed ''The Dean of Moderators'' by [[Bernard Shaw (journalist)|Bernard Shaw, formerly of CNN]], Lehrer has moderated 12 Presidential Debates.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Associated Press|title=Jim Lehrer: 'The Dean of Moderators'|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/6133830/|work=MSNBC.com|date=29 September 2004|accessdate=26 September 2008}}</ref>

Lehrer hosted the [[First U.S. presidential debate of 2012|first U.S. Presidential Debate]] for the [[United States presidential election, 2012|2012 U.S. Presidential general election]]. He originally had sworn off moderating any debates after 2008; however, the Commission on Presidential Debates persisted, and he accepted as he was interested in the new format.<ref>{{Cite web |first1=Brian |last1=Stelter |first2=Michael D. |last2=Shear |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/18/us/criticism-greets-list-of-debate-moderators.html |title=Criticism Greets List of Debate Moderators |publisher=''The New York Times, USA'' |date=4 October 2012 |accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref> The debate was held at the [[University of Denver]], [[Denver]], Colorado, and covered domestic policy issues.  Coming out of semi-retirement to moderate his 12th Presidential Debate, while he was criticized on [[social media]] and in the press for his lack of control and open-ended questions, he was praised for letting the candidates have some control in the debate on their own terms.<ref>{{cite news | first = David | last = Bauder | title = Tough Reviews for Jim Lehrer as Debate Moderator |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Tough-reviews-for-Jim-Lehrer-as-debate-moderator-3917905.php | date = 4 October 2012 | publisher = ''Hearst Communications Inc.'' | work = San Francisco Chronicle, California, USA | accessdate = 4 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/decision2012/jim-lehrers-debate-performance-criticized-defended-and-analyzed/2012/10/04/62d09810-0e19-11e2-bb5e-492c0d30bff6_story.html |title=Jim Lehrer's Debate Performance Criticized, Defended, and Analyzed |publisher=''The Washington Post, USA'' |date=4 October 2012 |accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Lehrer is married to [[Kate Lehrer]], a novelist. They have three daughters and six grandchildren.<ref name="PBSbio" /> His father was a bus driver, who briefly operated a bus company. Lehrer is an avid [[bus enthusiast]], a hobbyist, and a collector of bus memorabilia—including depot signs, driver caps, and antique toy buses.<ref>Lehrer, Jim - "''A Bus of My Own''", New York: Putnam - 1992. {{ISBN|0-399-13765-3}}.</ref><ref>Hari Sreenivasan - "Jim Lehrer's 'Super' Office Tour", ''On the Road'', PBS, 16 April 2010.[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/2010/04/jim-lehrers-super-office-tour.html]</ref> As a college student in the 1950s, he worked as a [[Trailways]] Ticket Agent in [[Victoria, Texas]]. He is a supporter of the [http://www.pacbus.org/ Pacific Bus Museum] in [[Williams, California]], and the [http://www.visitpa.com/pa-museums/museum-bus-transportation Museum of Bus Transportation] in [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=PBSbio />

Lehrer is a prolific writer and has authored numerous novels, as well as having penned several plays, screenplays, and three personal memoirs. His book, ''Top Down'', is a novel based on the events surrounding the Kennedy assassination.<ref>Lehrer, Jim - "''Top Down: A Novel of the Kennedy Assassination''", New York: Random House, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1-4000-6916-3}}.</ref> His most recent play, ''Bell'', was produced by the [[National Geographic Society]] as part of their 125th anniversary celebration.

