'''The Tucson Five''' was a group of house-mates from [[Los Angeles]] who were, despite a lack of evidence, alleged by the [[FBI]] to have been participants in the [[Weather Underground]]. Their case is notable because of the way in which grand jury proceedings and contempt of court charges were used against the group by [[Guy L. Goodwin]] of the [[United States Department of Justice]], ultimately leading to a successful appeal to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] by one member of the group. The case is additionally notable because the FBI breached the group's [[attorney-client privilege]] via [[wiretap]]s and [[black bag job]]s.<ref name="Burrough 2016">{{cite web | last=Burrough | first=Bryan | title=Days of Rage | website=Google Books | date=23 June 2016 | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Days_of_Rage.html?id=QPUVBAAAQBAJ&q=swearingen | accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JGj0eiWGGFIC|title=FBI Secrets|first=M. Wesley|last=Swearingen|date=1 January 1995|publisher=South End Press|accessdate=1 July 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ErCHQ4so9VEC|title=The Dangers of Dissent: The FBI and Civil Liberties since 1965|first=Ivan|last=Greenberg|date=14 October 2010|publisher=Lexington Books|accessdate=1 July 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=p0yV-i0RtgcC&q=%22the%20tucson%20five%22&dq=%22the%20tucson%20five%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjykrrIgtHNAhVC1xoKHQSbD-sQ6AEIQTAG|title=Grand Jury Reform: Hearings Before the Subcommittee on Immigration, Citizenship, and International Law of the Committee on the Judiciary, House of Representatives, Ninety-fifth Congress, First Session, on H.R. 94 ...|first=United States Congress House Committee on the Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration, Citizenship, and International|last=Law|date=1 January 1977|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|accessdate=1 July 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>
